  "prompt": "What does namespace mean in Java?",
  "response": "In Java, the concept of namespace is primarily implemented through packages. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Basic Definition\n```java\npackage com.example.myproject;  // This is a namespace declaration\n\npublic class MyClass {\n    // Class implementation\n}\n```\n\n2. Key Characteristics of Namespaces (Packages) in Java:\n- Provide a way to organize and group related classes and interfaces\n- Prevent naming conflicts\n- Control access to classes\n- Provide a hierarchical structure for organizing code\n\n3. Creating and Using Namespaces\n```java\n// Declaring a namespace\npackage com.company.project;\n\n// Importing from a namespace\nimport com.company.project.SomeClass;\n```\n\n4. Benefits:\n- Avoid name collisions\n- Improve code organization\n- Provide better access control\n- Enable modular development\n\n5. Fully Qualified Name Example:\n```java\n// Full namespace path\ncom.company.project.MyClass myObject = new com.company.project.MyClass();\n\n// Or using import\nimport com.company.project.MyClass;\nMyClass myObject = new MyClass();\n```\n\n6. Nested Namespaces\n```java\npackage com.company.project.submodule;\n```\n\nUnlike some languages (like C#), Java doesn't have a direct \"namespace\" keyword, but packages serve the same fundamental purpose of creating logical groupings and preventing naming conflicts.",
